{# ══ Review ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call reviewSection() %}

<div class="accordion mb-3" id="unit05-review">
  {% call accordion("rev-05-a", "Summary: How do you distinguish inheritance, aggregation, and composition?") %}
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Inheritance</strong> — is-a relationship. Hollow triangle arrowhead pointing to parent.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggregation</strong> — has-a (weak). Parts can exist independently. Hollow diamond at whole end.</li>
    <li><strong>Composition</strong> — has-a (strong). Parts cannot exist without the whole. Filled diamond at whole end.</li>
  </ul>
  {% endcall %}

  {% call accordion("rev-05-b", "Summary: Why do cohesion and coupling matter for long-term software quality?") %}
  <p>
    Software is never finished — it is always being changed. A system with high cohesion and
    low coupling can be changed safely: modifying one class does not force changes elsewhere,
    and each class is simple enough to understand and test in isolation.
  </p>
  <p>
    A system with low cohesion and high coupling accumulates technical debt — the cost of
    changes grows over time until the system becomes too fragile to modify. Good class design
    keeps that cost low.
  </p>
  {% endcall %}
</div>

